               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420131-name-1359" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1359" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1359" type="surname" value="HUGHES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1359" type="given" value="SUSAN"></interp>SUSAN HUGHES</persName>
                  </hi>. I was in Shrewsbury in 1832—I knew the prisoner at Mr. Eaton's—the prisoner asked me to go to church—I said, "Ann Davis would rather go"—he was often talking of that marriage—the ac<lb></lb>count I gave in the last case is correct.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420131-name-1360" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1360" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1360" type="surname" value="BARNES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1360" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM BARNES</persName>
                  </hi>. I produce a copy of the marriage register, and it is correct—the prisoner called on me, and said he was married at St. Chad's, on the 16th of July, 1823, to Emma Fox, a dress-maker, by whom he had three children, that one was dead, and that he left his wife and two children in Manchester.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420131-name-1361" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1361" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1361" type="surname" value="TURNER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1361" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE TURNER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am parish clerk of St. Peter, Walworth, in St. Mary, Newington. I have the marriage register, in which there is an entry that on the "18th February, 1840, (No. 284) Richard Light and Hannah Butlin, of full age, widower and spinster, by trade a grocer, were married in this church. (Witness)</p>
               <p>"<hi rend="smallCaps">GEORGE TURNER, ANN BAILEY</hi>."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
